  "_dft": {
    "_doc": "Four LFSRs at four widths and four polynomial qualities, lighting up every status the DFT panel's PATTERN GENERATORS section knows how to render:\n\n  • LFSR_3   — 3-bit, taps [2,0] (x³+x+1).  Primitive, period = 7 = 2³-1, but Q is wired to nothing → amber 'unused'.\n  • LFSR_4   — 4-bit, taps [3,0] (x⁴+x+1).  Primitive, period = 15. Q drives SFF_4.TI → green 'BIST source'. The canonical small-design BIST pattern source.\n  • LFSR_6   — 6-bit, taps [5,3].          Non-primitive (the polynomial factors), period = 14 of a possible 63 → amber 'sub-max'. Same Fibonacci shape as the others but the orbit is short — the kind of mistake a fresh designer makes when picking taps from intuition instead of a primitive-polynomial table.\n  • LFSR_8   — 8-bit, taps [7,5,4,3].      Primitive (CRC-8 lineage, x⁸+x⁶+x⁵+x⁴+1), period = 255. Q drives SFF_8.TI → green 'BIST source'. Wider state, much richer test pattern.\n\nOpen the DFT panel (T) and scroll to PATTERN GENERATORS. Each LFSR is its own collapsible card. Click the ✎ next to any field (width, seed, shape) to edit. Try changing LFSR_6's taps to [5,4] and watch the period jump from 14 to 63 — that's why primitive polynomial tables exist."
  },
